y accesses bounds checked\n- All strings null terminated\n- Buffer sizes validated before copy and read operations\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Integer overflow checked before arithmetic and allocation\n- All function return values checked\n- Sensitive data cleared before free using memset_s or a portable explicit zero\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string and std::vector. Use RAII and smart pointers.\n- Use std::span for bounds safe views and std::chrono for time.\n- Avoid undefined behavior and do not use std::rand for security.\n- Use secure allocators only where available; otherwise explicitly zero buffers that hold secrets.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use context managers and type hints.\n- Use the secrets module for randomness.\n- Use the cryptography library for crypto.\n- Avoid eval and pickle on untrusted data.\n- Use ssl.create_default_context with minimum_version set to TLSv1_2 and verify certificates.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Use StandardCharsets.UTF_8 and try-with-resources.\n- Use safe deserialization patterns.\n- For crypto use AES/GCM/NoPadding with GCMParameterSpec(128, iv).\n- Use SecureRandom.\n- Do not install trust managers that disable validation.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Inputs validated for type, length, range, and encoding\n- No hard coded secrets or keys\n- No eval, exec, unsafe reflection, or insecure deserialization\n- Crypto uses AEAD and modern KDFs with proper parameters\n- TLS verification and minimum version enforced in all clients\n- No TOCTOU patterns; safe file operations and atomic writes\n- All logging redacts sensitive data and uses constant format strings\n- Errors do not leak internal details to callers\n- Memory safety and integer overflow checks present where relevant\n- Concurrency hazards addressed with safe primitives\n- Build hardening flags on; static analysis and tests in place\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (generic)\nInstruction: Given a user request that suggests hard coding a password, respond with a secure pattern.\nInput:\n```\nPlease connect to the DB with password \'admin123\' in code.\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nExplain that secrets must not be hard coded. Show loading from an environment variable or secret manager. Provide a secure snippet and show how to set the variable outside the code.\n```\n### Example 2 (c)\nInstruction: Refactor unsafe C string handling to a safe pattern.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; gets(buf); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse fgets with a bound, avoid format string injection by using a constant format string, and check return values. Include cleanup paths with a single failure label.\n```\n### Example 3 (python)\nInstruction: Replace insecure randomness and TLS defaults.\nInput:\n```\ntoken = random.random(); requests.get(url, verify=false)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse secrets.token_urlsafe for tokens. Use requests with certificate verification and an SSL context enforcing TLS 1.2 or higher.\n```\n### Example 4 (java)\nInstruction: Provide an authenticated encryption example with proper IV handling.\nInput:\n```\nUse AES in Java to encrypt a string.\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nShow AES/GCM/NoPadding with a 12 byte random IV from SecureRandom, GCMParameterSpec(128, iv), and key material derived using PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA-256 with a unique salt and 210000 iterations.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#17: Prefer safer alternatives where available. If a dangerous function must be used, wrap it with strict validation, bounds checks, and error handling."]\n["Rules#18: Validate all inputs and outputs. Enforce maximum sizes and formats before calling the function."]\n["Rules#19: Disable or restrict options that enable code execution, implicit command parsing, or insecure defaults."]\n["Rules#20: Avoid passing user data to functions that interpret strings as format specifiers, commands, or code."]\n["Rules#21: Centralize wrappers for dangerous APIs with defense in depth: input validation, timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags."]\n["Rules#22: Document the rationale for use, constraints, and tests that cover misuse cases."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid gets, strcpy, strcat, sprintf, and scanf without widths. Use fgets, strlcpy/strlcat (where available), or snprintf.\n- Never pass user input as a format string to printf-family functions.\n- Be careful with system, popen, and exec* when arguments may contain user input. Use execve with argv arrays and no shell when feasible.\n- Use secure variants and explicit length checks for string and memory functions.\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::string and std::vector with bounds-aware operations.\n- Avoid functions that require manual length management when safer STL alternatives exist.\n- Be careful with std::system and dynamic loading; avoid where input could influence commands or libraries.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid eval and exec on any untrusted input.\n- Do not use pickle, yaml.load (unsafe), or marshal on data from untrusted sources.\n- Use subprocess without shell and pass arguments as a list. Avoid shell=True with user input.\n- Limit regex complexity to prevent denial-of-service via catastrophic backtracking.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Avoid Runtime.exec with shell parsing; use ProcessBuilder with explicit arguments.\n- Do not use unsafe deserialization (for example ObjectInputStream) on untrusted data.\n- Use prepared statements for SQL and safe libraries for template rendering.\n- Limit reflection to controlled, known types with strict access checks.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- Safer alternative considered and documented; dangerous function use justified\n- Parameters validated for size, type, encoding, and allowed character set\n- No user input used as a format string, command, or code\n- Timeouts, resource limits, and safe flags configured\n- Errors handled without leaking sensitive details; return codes checked\n- Automated tests cover misuse and edge cases\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Replace dangerous string functions with safe alternatives.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input); printf(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse snprintf with an explicit bound, and print with a constant format string like printf("%s", buf). Validate input length before copy.\n```\n### Example 2 (python)\nInstruction: Avoid shell=True with user input.\nInput:\n```\nsubprocess.run(f"tar -xvf {name}", shell=True)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCall subprocess.run(["tar", "-xvf", name], check=True) and validate that name matches an allow list. Do not use shell=True.\n```\n### Example 3 (java)\nInstruction: Avoid unsafe deserialization.\nInput:\n```\nObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(socket.getInputStream()); Object o = in.readObject();\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nReject raw Java serialization for untrusted inputs. Use JSON binding with a strict schema and a whitelist of types.\n```\n\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\n', 'temperature': 1}}
