th string concatenation.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Validate with Bean Validation (Jakarta Validation) or explicit checks. Enforce size, pattern, and range.\n- Use prepared statements for SQL. Avoid concatenating user input into queries.\n- Do not use deserialization on untrusted data. Prefer JSON binding with strict schemas and known types.\n- Sanitize or encode data before rendering into HTML, XML, or logs.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All inputs validated for type, format, encoding, length, and range\n- Strict schemas used for structured data; unsafe features disabled\n- No string concatenation used to build queries or commands\n- Normalization done before validation for paths and URLs\n- Validation errors return generic messages; detailed info goes only to secure logs\n- Logging uses constant format strings; sensitive data redacted\n- Dangerous parsers and dynamic execution features are not used on untrusted input\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (generic)\nInstruction: Validate user input before processing.\nInput:\n```\nPOST /signup { "email": "user@@example..com", "age": "-5" }\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nReject the request with specific field errors. Enforce a canonical email pattern, numeric age within range, and correct types. Do not process downstream until inputs pass validation.\n```\n### Example 2 (python)\nInstruction: Validate and bind JSON request data safely.\nInput:\n```\ndata = request.get_json(); user = create_user(data)\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse a schema (for example pydantic) to parse and validate fields, enforce length and pattern constraints, and reject unknown fields before calling create_user.\n```\n### Example 3 (c)\nInstruction: Parse an integer from a string safely.\nInput:\n```\nint n = atoi(buf);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nUse strtol with end pointer and errno checks, verify range, reject trailing characters, and handle errors without undefined behavior.\n```\n\n## General Mitigation\n["Rules#34: Perform explicit bounds checks before every read or write. Use size-aware APIs and track lengths separately from buffers."]\n["Rules#35: Validate all size calculations for integer overflow before allocation and before memcpy or similar operations."]\n["Rules#36: Initialize pointers and buffers. Ensure strings are null terminated where required by the API."]\n["Rules#37: Prefer safe library functions or wrappers that take buffer size and return explicit status codes."]\n["Rules#38: Grow buffers dynamically only up to a defined maximum. Refuse inputs that exceed limits to avoid excessive memory use."]\n["Rules#39: Use memory-safe abstractions where available. Avoid manual pointer arithmetic unless necessary and well reviewed."]\n["Rules#40: On failure, do not use partially initialized buffers. Clear sensitive data before free using a guaranteed zeroization API."]\n["Rules#41: When reading from streams (for example fread or memchr workflows), bound the read by the remaining buffer size and verify the returned count before use."]\n\n## C Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Check all allocation results for NULL and compute sizes with overflow checks (for example size_t n; if (n > SIZE_MAX / elem_size) fail).\n- Use snprintf, strnlen, memcpy with checked lengths, and memmove when regions may overlap.\n- Use fgets with a bound for input. Avoid gets and scanf without widths.\n- Validate indices and pointer arithmetic against buffer length. Use openat and fstat when validating file descriptors rather than path strings.\n- After fread, verify the number of bytes read before processing; when using memchr, check results and remaining length.\n\n### Checklist\n- All pointers initialized to NULL or valid memory\n- All allocations checked for NULL\n- All copies and reads bounded by destination size\n- All strings explicitly null terminated where required\n- Integer overflow checks before size arithmetic and allocation\n- Each function return value checked\n- All allocated memory freed exactly once\n- Sensitive data cleared before free\n\n## CPP Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Prefer std::vector, std::array, std::string, and std::span for bounds-aware access.\n- Use at() for bounds-checked indexing when feasible. Validate all indices from untrusted input.\n- Avoid raw new and delete. Use RAII and smart pointers. Verify sizes when constructing containers from external data.\n- When interfacing with C APIs, validate sizes and convert safely to size_t.\n\n## PYTHON Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Native Python enforces bounds on lists and bytearray, but vulnerabilities arise at library boundaries.\n- When using struct, array, memoryview, or NumPy, validate lengths and shapes before operations.\n- For I/O, limit reads, check returned sizes, and avoid slicing beyond the received data.\n\n## JAVA Specific Mitigation\n### Guidance\n- Array accesses are bounds checked, but ByteBuffer, NIO, and native code can introduce risks.\n- Validate lengths before System.arraycopy and ByteBuffer operations.\n- When using JNI or unsafe memory operations, enforce strict bounds and validate all sizes.\n\n## Code Review Checklist\n- All reads and writes guarded by explicit bounds checks\n- All size arithmetic protected against integer overflow\n- Length tracked separately from buffer capacity and validated\n- Safe, size-aware APIs used; dangerous functions avoided\n- Buffer growth capped by a defined maximum; oversize inputs rejected\n- All return values checked; partial reads handled correctly\n- Sensitive data wiped before free; no double frees\n\n## Finetune Examples\n### Example 1 (c)\nInstruction: Fix an overflow when copying input into a fixed-size buffer.\nInput:\n```\nchar buf[64]; strcpy(buf, input);\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nCheck the length of input, refuse if it exceeds sizeof(buf) - 1, then use snprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), "%s", input) to copy safely and enforce null termination.\n```\n### Example 2 (cpp)\nInstruction: Guard vector indexing with untrusted indices.\nInput:\n```\nauto v = std::vector<int>(n); return v[i];\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nValidate 0 <= i && i < v.size() before access, or use v.at(i) to get bounds-checked access and handle exceptions appropriately.\n```\n### Example 3 (python)\nInstruction: Safely read from a stream into a buffer.\nInput:\n```\ndata = f.read(); header = data[:8]\n```\nIdeal Output:\n```\nRead at most the needed amount with a cap, for example data = f.read(8); ensure len(data) == 8 before parsing.\n```\n\n\n3. Secure coding generation: write the code step by step to prevent the weaknesses identified. Document why each security measure is necessary with inline comments\n4. Code review: review the generated code line by line to confirm there are no weaknesses.\n5. Secure code output: output the final corrected code only, inside the four code blocks.\n', 'temperature': 1}}
